# Orchestrator — Run Setup

## Project identity
- **slug:** `edtech-school-connect-web-portal`
- **run dir:** `upwork-runs/edtech-school-connect-web-portal/`
- **demo path (local):** `../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/edtech-school-connect-web-portal/`
- **demo URL (live):** `https://michaelwegter.com/demos/edtech-school-connect-web-portal/`
- **work-sample route:** `/work-samples/edtech-school-connect-web-portal`
- **target feature richness:** 10 / 10 (full-featured, production-quality, several real working features)

## What the client actually wants (startup brief)
A web developer to build an **MVP of an "EdTech School Connect" portal** whose
core purpose is **two-way communication between schools and parents**, with
**real-time updates on student performance and activities**. They want a
**functional prototype delivered fast**.

- Engagement: hourly, less than 30 hrs/week, 1 to 3 months, ongoing project,
  intermediate level, "mix of experience and value."
- Mandatory skills listed: **PHP, Web Development.** Nice-to-have: JavaScript, HTML5.
- They are in MVP stage and explicitly value a working prototype over polish promises.

### Reading between the lines
- "School Connect" portals are a known category (think ClassDojo, Bloomz,
  Seesaw, ParentSquare, Schoology/PowerSchool parent portals). The differentiator
  the posting emphasizes is **communication + real-time performance/activity
  updates**, so the hero flow should be the parent/teacher loop, not admin CRUD.
- **PHP is the stated stack** but the deliverable for THIS workflow is a
  same-origin static demo on michaelwegter.com (no PHP runtime on GH Pages). The
  proposal must address PHP head-on: the demo proves the product and UX; the
  cover letter states clearly that production would be built on PHP (the demo
  uses a JS/static front end + optional mw-backend for live data because it has
  to run on a static host) and that Michael is fluent in the PHP equivalent.
  Do NOT pretend the demo is PHP. Position it as a clickable, real-data product
  prototype that maps 1:1 to a PHP/Laravel build.
- Audience = two distinct roles (parent and teacher/school). The demo should let
  a reviewer experience BOTH sides, ideally via role switching or seeded logins.

## Plan of attack (phase ordering)
Recommended graph (the `with-deploy` + `with-ceo` layout fits well here because
there is a backend opportunity and richness is maxed):

`intake -> planner -> ceo -> researcher -> demo-builder -> deploy -> deploy-test -> media-capture -> proposal-writer -> evaluator`

Pair the CEO after planner (and again after demo-builder if the studio layout
allows) to keep ambition aligned with the 10/10 target.

### Guidance per downstream phase
- **intake:** Capture every explicit requirement as a checklist item:
  (1) school↔parent communication, (2) real-time student performance updates,
  (3) real-time activity updates, (4) functional MVP/prototype, (5) PHP stack
  acknowledgment, (6) fast delivery. Flag the PHP-vs-static-demo tension so the
  proposal-writer addresses it explicitly. Note the two user roles.
- **planner:** This is a **full build, not a prototype** (richness 10). Choose a
  hero feature = the real-time parent↔teacher communication + performance feed.
  At most 2 supporting features (caps still apply): e.g. (a) a gradebook /
  performance dashboard with charts, (b) an activity/announcements feed or
  attendance tracker. Strongly recommend wiring **mw-backend** with a new
  blueprint so updates are genuinely real-time/persistent (a working DB-backed
  messaging + performance feed sells the "real-time" claim far better than mock
  data). Seed a demo parent account AND a demo teacher account; record creds.
  Define a **bespoke EdTech design system** (friendly, trustworthy, school-brand
  feel — warm/approachable, accessible contrast, NOT michaelwegter.com's dark
  gallery theme). Produce the requirement→feature traceability matrix.
- **researcher:** Pull real conventions from leading school-parent comms apps
  (ClassDojo, ParentSquare, Seesaw, Bloomz, Schoology parent view): typical
  layout, color/tone (clean, bright, reassuring), feature set, role separation.
  Identify the exact existing app+blueprint to clone — clone `spotify_blueprint.py`
  for the backend scaffold and an existing self-contained demo for the front end.
- **demo-builder:** Build into the demo path above. If backend greenlit, add one
  blueprint (messages + performance + activities), register in `server.py`, keep
  CORS open, do not touch auth/DB schema/other blueprints beyond what's needed.
  Role switching or dual login so reviewers see both parent and teacher sides.
- **deploy / deploy-test:** Push both repos if a blueprint was added; Playwright
  the live site including login on both roles and a full send-message→see-update
  round trip; emit VERDICT.
- **media-capture:** Hero flow = a parent receiving/seeing a real-time performance
  update and exchanging a message with a teacher.
- **proposal-writer:** Tailor deck + one-pager to the EdTech/school audience using
  the demo's design language. Embed the live demo link in BOTH cover letter and
  deck. Explicitly map each requirement to what the demo shows. Address PHP.
- **evaluator:** Enforce the hard gates; confirm PHP tension is handled honestly.

## Quality guidance / risks to watch
- **Real-time means real-time.** With richness 10, do not fake it with setTimeout
  shuffling static JSON only. Prefer a backend-backed feed (polling or SSE) so a
  message sent on the teacher side actually appears on the parent side. This is
  the single most credible thing the demo can prove.
- **Two roles must both be experienceable** in the live demo without friction.
- **Privacy/trust framing matters in EdTech** (student data, FERPA-style
  sensibilities). The design and copy should feel safe and parent-friendly; the
  proposal can note awareness of student-data privacy.
- **Honesty on stack.** Never claim the demo is PHP. Frame it as a product
  prototype that translates directly to the client's PHP/Laravel target.
- **Writing rules:** no em/en dashes anywhere; Michael's voice; concrete, not
  generic. Cohesive bespoke design across demo + one-pager + deck.
- **Budget:** 1 hero + ≤2 supporting features, ≤~12 files touched in the demo,
  3-min build timeout, ≤~6 research fetches, reflection retries ≤2. Disk is
  memory — pass file paths between phases, not contents.

## Definition of done (carry forward)
All 6 hard gates in CLAUDE.md must hold: every brief requirement in cover letter
AND demo/deck; demo builds with no first-paint console errors; demo resolves
locally and live route 200; demo link in cover letter AND deck; cohesive bespoke
EdTech design with no em/en dashes; passing `eval-report.md` with empty/accepted
fix list.

Setup complete. Next step: intake.
